context: In the course of the <b3_0>10th century<b3_0/>, the initially destructive incursions of Norse war bands into the rivers of France evolved into more permanent encampments that included local women and personal property. The Duchy of Normandy, which began in <a0_0><a0_1><a0_2>911<a0_2/><a0_1/><a0_0/> as a fiefdom, was established by the <b4_0>treaty of Saint-Clair-sur-Epte<b4_0/> between <a1_0><a1_1><a1_2>King Charles III<a1_2/><a1_1/><a1_0/> of West Francia and the famed Viking ruler <b5_0>Rollo<b5_0/>, and was situated in the former Frankish kingdom of Neustria. The treaty offered Rollo and his men the French lands between the river <a2_1>Epte<a2_1/> and the Atlantic coast in exchange for their protection against <b6_0>further Viking incursions.<b6_0/> The area corresponded to the northern part of present-day Upper Normandy down to the river <a2_0><a2_2>Seine<a2_2/><a2_0/>, but the Duchy would eventually extend west beyond the Seine. The territory was roughly equivalent to the old province of Rouen, and reproduced the Roman administrative structure of Gallia Lugdunensis II (part of the former Gallia Lugdunensis).
